        'The International Astronomical Union officially defined the 88 modern constellations in 1930, creating a map that divides the sky into distinct regions.',
        'The stars in a constellation are not actually close together — they only appear grouped from our viewpoint on Earth; in reality they may be hundreds of light-years apart.',
